Professional EKG Template Layout  
A clinical-grade report should be structured to allow for a "separate, signed, written, and retrievable report" as required by [CMS](https://www.cms.gov/medicare-coverage-database/view/article.aspx?articleId=57326) and [CPT 93010 guidelines](https://ergjax.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/ECG-Interpretation-CPT-Code-93010-Coding-Charting.pdf).

| Section  | Field Name | Type/Requirements |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Patient ID |  |  |
| Vital Signs | Heart Rate (bpm) | Numeric |
|  | Blood Pressure (mmHg) | Systolic / Diastolic |
|  | BP Context | Position (Sitting/Supine) & Location (L/R arm) |
| EKG Intervals | PR Interval | Numeric (ms) — Normal: 120-200ms |
|  | QRS Duration | Numeric (ms) — Normal: \<120ms |
|  | QT / QTc | Numeric (ms) |
|  | QRS Axis | Degrees (e.g., \-30° to \+90°) |
| Interpretation | Rhythm | Dropdown (e.g., Sinus, AFib, Bradycardia) |
|  | Waveform Findings | Checkboxes (ST-elevation, T-wave inversion) |
|  | Comparison | Text: "Compared to prior EKG on \[Date\]" |
| Clinical Report | Impression | Summary of findings and clinical impact |
|  | Medical Necessity | Why the test was ordered (e.g., "Chest Pain") |
| Auth | Physician Signature | [Legible/Electronic Signature & Date](https://med.noridianmedicare.com/web/jeb/topics/documentation-requirements/echocardiogram) |

2\. Common ICD-10 Codes for Justification  
Billing for an EKG (CPT 93000-93010) requires a linked diagnosis code that supports medical necessity. 

* Symptoms/Reasons for Order:  
  * R07.9: [Chest pain, unspecified](https://www.outsourcestrategies.com/blog/electrocardiography-ekg-coding-accurate-hospital-ed-billing/)  
  * R00.2: Palpitations  
  * R55: Syncope (fainting) and collapse  
  * R06.02: Shortness of breath  
* Heart Conditions Found:  
  * I10: Essential (primary) [hypertension](https://firstcoastbillinggroup.com/ekg-billing-and-reimbursement/)  
  * I48.91: Atrial fibrillation, unspecified  
  * I44.0: Atrioventricular block, first degree  
  * I21.9: Acute myocardial infarction (unspecified site)  
  * I25.2: Old myocardial infarction  
* Other Findings:  
  * R94.31: [Abnormal electrocardiogram (ECG/EKG)](https://www.aapc.com/codes/icd-10-codes/R94.31)  
  * Z01.810: Encounter for pre-procedural cardiovascular examination 

3\. Compliance Checklist

* Three-Element Rule: For a billable interpretation, the provider must comment on at least three of the following: Rate, Rhythm, Axis, Intervals, Comparison, or Clinical Summary. [Source: AAPC](https://www.aapc.com/discuss/threads/ekg-interpretation-documentation-requirements.39398/).  
* Interfaced Data: If possible, include a PDF/Image Upload field for the actual 12-lead tracing. A numeric summary alone is often considered a "review" rather than a full "interpretation and report." 

To finalize your clinical form, you must distinguish between the technical act of performing the test and the professional act of reading it. In the U.S., these are billed using CPT (Current Procedural Terminology) codes.  
1\. Standard EKG CPT Codes  
If the doctor is performing the test and interpreting it in the same office, they use the "Global" code. If they are only reading a test done elsewhere, they use a modifier.

| CPT Code | Service Type | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 93000 | Global | The complete EKG: includes the tracing (equipment/tech) and the interpretation/report (doctor). |
| 93005 | Technical | Only the tracing. Used by hospitals or clinics that own the machine but don't provide the final MD report. |
| 93010 | Professional | Only the [Interpretation and Report](https://www.aapc.com/discuss/threads/ekg-interpretation-documentation-requirements.39398/). This is the most common code for doctors filling out your form. |

2\. Codes for Specialized Measurements  
Since your form also captures Heart Rate and Blood Pressure, these are usually bundled into the Evaluation and Management (E/M) office visit codes (99202–99215). However, specific rhythm monitoring has its own codes:

* 93040: Rhythm ECG, 1–3 leads; with interpretation and report (used for quick rhythm strips rather than a full 12-lead EKG).  
* 93224: Holter Monitor (up to 48 hours); includes recording, scanning analysis, and report.

3\. Essential Documentation for CPT 93010  
To legally bill the Professional Component (93010) via your form, the American College of Cardiology and CMS require the "Separate, Signed Report" to include:

1. Patient Identification: Name and DOB.  
2. Findings: At least 3 of the elements mentioned previously (Rhythm, Rate, Axis, etc.).  
3. Clinical Comparison: A note stating if it was compared to a previous EKG.  
4. Signature: The interpreting physician's physical or digital signature.

4\. Form Design Tip: The "Modifier 26"  
If your digital form is being used by a consultant who only interprets the data but didn't touch the patient, ensure the billing output attaches Modifier 26 to the CPT code. This tells the insurance company to pay only for the "Professional" work.  
Would you like me to provide a JSON structure or database schema example for how to store these clinical EKG fields and CPT codes?

To help you build a robust database for this clinical record, I’ve structured a schema that separates the vitals (frequently measured) from the EKG report (a formal medical interpretation).  
1\. Recommended Database Schema (SQL/Relational)  
This structure ensures you can store the "stream" of specific EKG metrics while maintaining a link to the billing codes and the physician's narrative.  
sql

```
-- Table for core vitals (HR, BP)
CREATE TABLE PatientVitals (
    vital_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    patient_id INT NOT NULL,
    recorded_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    heart_rate_bpm INT,
    systolic_mmhg INT,
    diastolic_mmhg INT,
    patient_position VARCHAR(50), -- e.g., Sitting, Supine
    arm_used VARCHAR(10),        -- e.g., Left, Right
    recorded_by_user_id INT      -- Technician ID
);

-- Table for formal EKG Interpretation (CPT 93010)
CREATE TABLE EKGInterpretations (
    ekg_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    patient_id INT NOT NULL,
    vital_id INT REFERENCES PatientVitals(vital_id), -- Links to the HR/BP taken at the time
    interpreted_at TIMESTAMP,
    
    -- Numeric Intervals (The "Measurements")
    pr_interval_ms INT,
    qrs_duration_ms INT,
    qt_interval_ms INT,
    qtc_interval_ms INT,
    qrs_axis_degrees INT,
    
    -- Qualitative Data
    rhythm_type VARCHAR(100),    -- e.g., "Normal Sinus", "Atrial Fibrillation"
    comparison_to_prior TEXT,    -- e.g., "No change from 2023-05-12"
    clinical_impression TEXT,    -- The doctor's final summary
    
    -- Billing & Compliance
    icd10_code VARCHAR(10),      -- e.g., "R07.9" (Chest Pain)
    cpt_code VARCHAR(10),        -- e.g., "93010"
    physician_signature_id INT,  -- Link to digital signature
    is_finalized BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE
);
```

Use code with caution.

Would you like the mathematical formula (Bazett or Fridericia) to auto-calculate the QTc interval in your form?  
To automate the QTc (Corrected QT interval) calculation in your form, you should use the Bazett Formula. While there are newer methods (like Fridericia), Bazett remains the clinical standard for most formal EKG reports \[1, 2\].  
The QT interval must be corrected because the heart's repolarization time changes based on the heart rate. Without correction, a "normal" QT at a fast heart rate might look "abnormal" at a slow one \[1, 3\].
